1
00:00:53,678 --> 00:01:00,602
ALL CHARACTERS, ORGANIZATIONS,
PLACES AND EVENTS ARE FICTIONAL

2
00:01:07,233 --> 00:01:08,735
Then keep your promise.

3
00:01:09,819 --> 00:01:10,862
The VIP.

4
00:01:13,656 --> 00:01:16,618
Who is the mastermind behind the attack?

5
00:01:18,536 --> 00:01:19,496
The VIP is...

6
00:01:25,668 --> 00:01:26,795
The VIP is...

7
00:01:27,754 --> 00:01:28,671
me.

8
00:01:33,259 --> 00:01:34,552
What did he say?

9
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:37,055
It's me.

10
00:01:38,807 --> 00:01:40,725
It's no one else.

11
00:01:41,893 --> 00:01:43,937
It's me,
the person sitting in front of you.

12
00:01:49,859 --> 00:01:54,364
Are you saying that you single-handedly
came up with the Assembly Building bombing

13
00:01:55,698 --> 00:01:57,283
and put it into action?

14
00:01:58,243 --> 00:02:03,039
I was against President Yang's policy
toward North Korea and planned it.

15
00:02:04,165 --> 00:02:07,502
I disapproved of his economic policy
and funded it.

16
00:02:09,337 --> 00:02:12,298
I despised him
for compromising with reality

17
00:02:12,549 --> 00:02:13,842
and took part in the bombing.

18
00:02:16,636 --> 00:02:18,096
President Yang's government

19
00:02:18,721 --> 00:02:21,015
wasn't welcome anywhere.

20
00:02:22,517 --> 00:02:23,685
Also,

21
00:02:24,894 --> 00:02:28,189
this nation created numerous people
that wanted to get revenge.

22
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:32,193
Those people willingly

23
00:02:32,694 --> 00:02:34,737
turned my plan into reality.

24
00:02:38,324 --> 00:02:39,367
However,

25
00:02:40,034 --> 00:02:41,911
the plan wouldn't have been complete

26
00:02:44,747 --> 00:02:46,541
if you weren't there at the beginning

27
00:02:47,709 --> 00:02:49,252
and end of the attack,

28
00:02:50,211 --> 00:02:51,796
President Park.

29
00:03:01,723 --> 00:03:02,891
Park Mu-jin.

30
00:03:04,726 --> 00:03:07,103
You helped complete the attack.

31
00:03:21,534 --> 00:03:24,245
President Park's press conference
is at 2 p.m. tomorrow, right?

32
00:03:24,329 --> 00:03:25,246
Yes.

33
00:03:26,247 --> 00:03:30,209
His term will end in a day,
24 hours to be exact.

34
00:03:30,668 --> 00:03:34,714
The press conference tomorrow
may be about his resignation,

35
00:03:34,797 --> 00:03:36,674
but it's actually to announce

36
00:03:37,342 --> 00:03:38,509
his candidacy.

37
00:03:40,261 --> 00:03:42,180
He stopped the coup

38
00:03:42,513 --> 00:03:45,391
and succeeded in arresting
the key suspect for the bombing.

39
00:03:46,351 --> 00:03:49,979
It's a relief he produced tangible results
at the end of his term.

40
00:03:50,605 --> 00:03:52,398
I hope it affects his ratings.

41
00:03:54,609 --> 00:03:55,610
Secretary Cha.

42
00:03:57,987 --> 00:04:01,574
We have today's approval ratings of

43
00:04:03,284 --> 00:04:04,369
the presidential candidates.

44
00:04:06,537 --> 00:04:08,414
How does it look?

45
00:04:12,210 --> 00:04:13,211
It's 11 percent.

46
00:04:24,430 --> 00:04:25,431
Well,

47
00:04:27,016 --> 00:04:28,643
it's okay.

48
00:04:28,726 --> 00:04:31,813
We can work harder
during the official campaign period.

49
00:04:33,564 --> 00:04:36,693
How much harder do we have to work?

50
00:04:37,694 --> 00:04:41,072
President Park is 11 percent
ahead of Assemblywoman Yun,

51
00:04:41,155 --> 00:04:44,450
becoming the most popular candidate
once again.

52
00:04:46,119 --> 00:04:48,037
When people found out
he was working with her,

53
00:04:48,121 --> 00:04:52,041
the approval rating seemed to have gone up
for his leadership.

54
00:04:53,543 --> 00:04:54,544
Goodness.

55
00:04:56,337 --> 00:04:58,715
I thought his approval rating
was 11 percent.

56
00:05:00,049 --> 00:05:01,217
Secretary Cha,

57
00:05:03,011 --> 00:05:05,138
you don't look surprised at all.

58
00:05:05,888 --> 00:05:08,558
You didn't even flinch.
Are you even human?

59
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:12,520
You both should hire lawyers.

60
00:05:12,603 --> 00:05:13,771
I'm going to sue you

61
00:05:14,439 --> 00:05:16,190
for attempted murder by gross negligence.

62
00:05:16,899 --> 00:05:18,568
You almost gave me a heart attack.

63
00:05:19,861 --> 00:05:21,487
Now he totally seems human.

64
00:05:23,239 --> 00:05:25,116
Did the president see the result?

65
00:05:25,199 --> 00:05:26,534
No.

66
00:05:27,285 --> 00:05:29,245
He hasn't returned yet.

67
00:05:29,954 --> 00:05:31,205
Did he go somewhere?

68
00:05:31,289 --> 00:05:33,958
I thought he didn't have anything
scheduled for this afternoon.

69
00:05:38,254 --> 00:05:39,505
What do you mean?

70
00:05:40,548 --> 00:05:42,633
How did I help complete the attack?

71
00:05:45,386 --> 00:05:47,555
It looks like you didn't see this coming

72
00:05:49,140 --> 00:05:51,559
when you're the biggest beneficiary
of the bombing.

73
00:05:58,399 --> 00:06:00,276
You said you're the VIP.

74
00:06:01,694 --> 00:06:02,570
Then...

75
00:06:03,446 --> 00:06:06,908
do you mean you used me
to complete the plan?

76
00:06:08,785 --> 00:06:09,744
I have

77
00:06:11,037 --> 00:06:12,914
never seen you before.

78
00:06:15,416 --> 00:06:17,043
The bombing didn't just occur

79
00:06:18,336 --> 00:06:20,505
because of the person that planned it.

80
00:06:21,798 --> 00:06:23,758
Someone who knew it would happen,

81
00:06:24,258 --> 00:06:26,427
but overlooked it, is also responsible.

82
00:06:28,971 --> 00:06:30,014
That person completed

83
00:06:30,723 --> 00:06:32,975
the attack through you.

84
00:06:33,142 --> 00:06:34,477
Who is this person?

85
00:06:36,145 --> 00:06:36,979
A pardon.

86
00:06:38,856 --> 00:06:41,025
I want you to promise me a pardon.

87
00:06:41,943 --> 00:06:44,112
Then I'll tell you who it is.

88
00:06:46,531 --> 00:06:48,199
I'll tell you

89
00:06:49,575 --> 00:06:51,661
who completed the bombing through you.

90
00:07:07,844 --> 00:07:12,098
DAY 31: THE LAST CHOICE
EPISODE 16

91
00:07:15,351 --> 00:07:16,644
Can I grant him a pardon?

92
00:07:17,103 --> 00:07:19,313
Yes, according to the 79th Amendment,
we could claim

93
00:07:19,397 --> 00:07:21,023
the lack of the right of arraignment.

94
00:07:21,107 --> 00:07:23,192
However, the problem is

95
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:25,820
that only the president
has the authority to grant a pardon.

96
00:07:27,572 --> 00:07:28,823
You only have a day left

97
00:07:28,906 --> 00:07:30,616
and the election is in a month.

98
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:34,454
Although you are currently
the leading candidate--

99
00:07:34,537 --> 00:07:35,580
My promise

100
00:07:36,122 --> 00:07:37,707
could be meaningless right now.

101
00:07:39,041 --> 00:07:42,753
Even if it is legally possible,
would it be the right choice?

102
00:07:43,463 --> 00:07:45,631
The bombing caused over 300 casualties.

103
00:07:45,715 --> 00:07:48,176
People were hurt beyond imagination.

104
00:07:48,801 --> 00:07:50,428
How could he ask for a pardon?

105
00:07:51,012 --> 00:07:52,972
He can never be forgiven.

106
00:07:54,307 --> 00:07:56,601
I think we could grant him a pardon

107
00:07:57,226 --> 00:07:59,437
if we could learn the truth
about the bombing.

108
00:08:00,271 --> 00:08:03,274
We should leave
a precise record in history

109
00:08:04,025 --> 00:08:05,776
on who and why
such a tragic attack occurred.

110
00:08:07,528 --> 00:08:09,030
I agree.

111
00:08:09,780 --> 00:08:13,367
If you can figure out
the whole story behind the attack,

112
00:08:14,410 --> 00:08:15,953
you should grant the pardon.

113
00:08:16,746 --> 00:08:19,957
If Mr. Kim starts talking today,

114
00:08:20,041 --> 00:08:21,959
you will have figured out the truth

115
00:08:22,043 --> 00:08:25,296
about the attack during your term, sir.

116
00:08:26,422 --> 00:08:28,591
I'm sure it'll be helpful
for the election.

117
00:08:32,803 --> 00:08:35,306
What do you think, Secretary Han?

118
00:08:38,893 --> 00:08:39,894
I'm against it.

119
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:45,107
The national sentiment
will be against granting the pardon.

120
00:08:45,316 --> 00:08:46,859
With the election coming up,

121
00:08:47,151 --> 00:08:50,571
it is dangerous to make a choice
contrary to the national sentiment.

122
00:08:51,531 --> 00:08:54,700
More than anything, Mayor Kang
and Assemblywoman Yun

123
00:08:55,201 --> 00:08:58,454
will bring the pardon up
for their campaign.

124
00:08:59,497 --> 00:09:00,873
They'll use legal terms

125
00:09:01,582 --> 00:09:03,209
and call it abuse of authority.

126
00:09:03,292 --> 00:09:05,753
They will try to cause controversy
during the election.

127
00:09:16,180 --> 00:09:18,849
You shouldn't look forward to a pardon,

128
00:09:19,976 --> 00:09:21,269
since the election is coming up.

129
00:09:22,645 --> 00:09:24,230
The leading candidate,

130
00:09:26,732 --> 00:09:27,733
as you should know,

131
00:09:27,817 --> 00:09:30,570
won't make decisions
that will affect his approval ratings.

132
00:09:32,738 --> 00:09:35,491
President Park only has a day
left in his term

133
00:09:35,616 --> 00:09:38,494
and you're locked up here.

134
00:09:39,287 --> 00:09:44,208
There is no reason for President Park
to rush to pardon you.

135
00:09:48,921 --> 00:09:53,092
So from now on, whether you
confess or put a deal on the table,

136
00:09:55,011 --> 00:09:57,096
you should talk to me.

137
00:10:12,528 --> 00:10:14,697
If I can't settle it legally,

138
00:10:15,948 --> 00:10:18,492
can't I settle it politically?

139
00:10:32,089 --> 00:10:33,841
What could President Park be up to?

140
00:10:34,925 --> 00:10:38,387
He wants to see me as a candidate,
not the mayor of Seoul.

141
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:43,309
He said he'd meet us
as a presidential candidate,

142
00:10:43,392 --> 00:10:44,977
not the president as well.

143
00:10:45,561 --> 00:10:46,562
I'm sure he has a reason.

144
00:10:49,065 --> 00:10:51,025
You want our consent for a pardon?

145
00:10:51,859 --> 00:10:54,070
Only the president has the right
to grant a pardon.

146
00:10:55,821 --> 00:10:58,032
Through the presidential election
in a month,

147
00:10:58,449 --> 00:10:59,700
one of us will probably

148
00:11:00,117 --> 00:11:01,452
become president.

149
00:11:05,331 --> 00:11:06,624
Whoever becomes president,

150
00:11:07,416 --> 00:11:10,002
if you promise Mr. Kim a pardon,

151
00:11:11,295 --> 00:11:13,464
he will start talking about the truth
behind the bombing.

152
00:11:13,547 --> 00:11:15,424
You want him to talk,

153
00:11:16,592 --> 00:11:18,761
but stop us from talking.

154
00:11:19,887 --> 00:11:22,598
Since the three presidential candidates
agreed to it,

155
00:11:22,681 --> 00:11:25,935
you don't want us using it
in our presidential campaign.

156
00:11:29,814 --> 00:11:31,857
Will you agree to it?

157
00:11:31,941 --> 00:11:33,275
Wait a minute.

158
00:11:36,153 --> 00:11:39,573
This places a heavy weight
on our shoulders politically.

159
00:11:40,574 --> 00:11:42,410
This isn't an amnesty
for a political prisoner.

160
00:11:42,493 --> 00:11:44,662
He's a heinous bomber.

161
00:11:45,162 --> 00:11:47,498
Why should we cut him a deal

162
00:11:48,666 --> 00:11:49,959
under our names?

163
00:11:54,088 --> 00:11:55,256
Because this bombing

164
00:11:55,339 --> 00:11:58,634
didn't begin from the spite
of one evil person.

165
00:12:00,177 --> 00:12:04,223
What's more important
than convicting him is to

166
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,810
uncover the truth of the bombing.

167
00:12:11,856 --> 00:12:12,815
Isn't it

168
00:12:14,525 --> 00:12:16,610
our responsibility to find out?

169
00:12:28,956 --> 00:12:30,749
AGREEMENT FOR PARDON

170
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:33,127
This will get Mr. Kim talking.

171
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:37,339
I'll make him talk,

172
00:12:37,798 --> 00:12:39,258
since we have this agreement.

173
00:12:40,676 --> 00:12:41,927
I hope you do.

174
00:13:01,113 --> 00:13:02,114
Answer me.

175
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:06,911
What do you mean President Park
completed the bombing?

176
00:13:19,298 --> 00:13:20,966
Why? What is it?

177
00:13:21,091 --> 00:13:22,885
What is it?

178
00:13:22,968 --> 00:13:24,094
Damn it.

179
00:13:36,857 --> 00:13:38,817
Call an ambulance immediately!

180
00:13:52,540 --> 00:13:54,333
-I'll go with him.
-Okay.

181
00:13:54,416 --> 00:13:56,335
We're going too. Follow us.

182
00:14:06,136 --> 00:14:07,263
Let's go.

183
00:14:19,567 --> 00:14:22,695
Could Mr. Kim have had
a chronic heart disease?

184
00:14:24,238 --> 00:14:26,282
Why is he suddenly having heart problems?

185
00:14:26,991 --> 00:14:28,200
It seems weird.

186
00:15:06,780 --> 00:15:08,115
He'll wake up soon.

187
00:16:19,812 --> 00:16:21,730
What is going on?

188
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:23,482
Turn the car around!

189
00:16:36,662 --> 00:16:39,540
Ji-won? We lost the ambulance.

190
00:16:39,623 --> 00:16:40,791
Find out where it is.

191
00:16:40,874 --> 00:16:43,544
Yes, we're at the traffic light
at the fork.

192
00:16:44,294 --> 00:16:45,421
Wait.

193
00:16:46,213 --> 00:16:48,007
My gosh. Do you not know how to drive?

194
00:16:48,090 --> 00:16:49,508
The ambulance...

195
00:16:49,591 --> 00:16:50,926
Move it.

196
00:16:51,010 --> 00:16:52,094
Move your car now!

197
00:16:52,845 --> 00:16:53,971
I can't locate it.

198
00:16:54,888 --> 00:16:57,391
-I don't see it.
-Move your car immediately.

199
00:17:17,536 --> 00:17:19,204
A helicopter will be here soon.

200
00:17:28,088 --> 00:17:29,506
Show me your hands! Don't move!

201
00:17:50,861 --> 00:17:53,947
There's a location Mr. Kim
used for a rendezvous nearby.

202
00:17:54,531 --> 00:17:56,617
It's where he met Oh Yeong-seok.

203
00:17:57,868 --> 00:17:59,119
Where is it?

204
00:18:41,370 --> 00:18:43,330
Mr. Kim!

205
00:18:53,590 --> 00:18:54,633
He's dead.

206
00:19:17,614 --> 00:19:19,408
PARK MU-JIN, KANG SANG-GU, YUN CHAN-GYEONG

207
00:19:19,491 --> 00:19:21,535
AGREEMENT FOR PARDON

208
00:19:22,119 --> 00:19:25,956
Mr. Kim was the biggest lead
we had on the mastermind.

209
00:19:26,123 --> 00:19:27,791
Someone silenced him.

210
00:19:28,208 --> 00:19:29,668
The accomplice in the Blue House must

211
00:19:30,252 --> 00:19:34,214
be someone that's more deeply involved
with the government than we think.

212
00:19:35,465 --> 00:19:37,301
It doesn't matter who it is.

213
00:19:37,467 --> 00:19:38,719
The important thing

214
00:19:39,011 --> 00:19:42,431
is for us to find a lead
on Mr. Kim's killer

215
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:44,183
before the press conference.

216
00:19:45,267 --> 00:19:46,518
Catching Mr. Kim alive

217
00:19:46,602 --> 00:19:50,397
is your biggest achievement
during your term, sir.

218
00:19:56,778 --> 00:19:57,613
Mr. Kang.

219
00:19:58,280 --> 00:19:59,156
Yes?

220
00:19:59,656 --> 00:20:01,283
Tell the NIS agents

221
00:20:02,784 --> 00:20:05,370
to report to the Blue House

222
00:20:05,871 --> 00:20:06,955
as soon as they find a lead.

223
00:20:17,466 --> 00:20:19,426
Is he still pleading the Fifth?

224
00:20:20,344 --> 00:20:22,679
Mr. Kim was given a drug
for cardiac arrest

225
00:20:22,763 --> 00:20:24,389
to get him out of the interrogation room.

226
00:20:25,015 --> 00:20:26,767
That agent's confidential files show that

227
00:20:26,934 --> 00:20:30,229
he was a spy sent to the North
at the same time as Mr. Kim.

228
00:20:31,396 --> 00:20:34,316
Why is he abusing skills
he obtained through work?

229
00:20:34,858 --> 00:20:38,612
So are you saying
he tried to help Mr. Kim run away,

230
00:20:38,695 --> 00:20:41,281
since they got through
a life-or-death situation together?

231
00:20:46,870 --> 00:20:47,996
This is from a CCTV

232
00:20:48,080 --> 00:20:50,082
near the location where Mr. Kim was shot.

233
00:20:53,335 --> 00:20:54,336
That face.

234
00:20:54,836 --> 00:20:56,255
It's Tae-ik,

235
00:20:57,214 --> 00:20:58,215
I mean Lee Gyeong-pyo.

236
00:20:58,507 --> 00:21:01,635
Did Lee Gyeong-pyo betray Mr. Kim,

237
00:21:01,760 --> 00:21:03,428
the VIP?

238
00:21:03,679 --> 00:21:04,554
Why?

239
00:21:05,514 --> 00:21:07,975
Someone wanted to help Mr. Kim run away

240
00:21:08,058 --> 00:21:10,227
from the NIS

241
00:21:10,310 --> 00:21:14,231
and someone wanted to silence him forever.

242
00:21:15,691 --> 00:21:18,777
What could Mr. Kim's relationship
with them be?

243
00:21:23,657 --> 00:21:25,117
The bombing didn't just occur

244
00:21:25,742 --> 00:21:27,828
because of the person that planned it.

245
00:21:27,911 --> 00:21:29,997
Someone who knew it would happen,

246
00:21:30,747 --> 00:21:32,833
but overlooked it, is also responsible.

247
00:21:32,916 --> 00:21:34,167
That person completed

248
00:21:34,918 --> 00:21:37,337
the attack through you.

249
00:21:39,715 --> 00:21:40,674
AGREEMENT FOR PARDON

250
00:21:44,177 --> 00:21:46,555
My report with a warning
regarding a possible attack

251
00:21:47,264 --> 00:21:50,559
was systematically buried
in the NIS as well as in the Blue House.

252
00:21:51,143 --> 00:21:52,144
Then...

253
00:21:54,021 --> 00:21:56,189
are you saying the person
who handed this top secret file

254
00:21:56,273 --> 00:21:58,025
over to those who orchestrated the attack

255
00:21:58,775 --> 00:22:01,236
was someone
inside the Yang administration?

256
00:22:18,295 --> 00:22:19,671
Up until now,

257
00:22:21,131 --> 00:22:23,425
we only thought of the accomplice
in the Blue House

258
00:22:23,967 --> 00:22:29,222
as the person who handed
the OP file over to the bomber.

259
00:22:29,306 --> 00:22:30,807
That's right.

260
00:22:31,683 --> 00:22:34,102
If someone overlooked the bombing
even when he knew about it

261
00:22:35,395 --> 00:22:39,691
and covered up the warning
against the attack,

262
00:22:41,234 --> 00:22:43,570
wouldn't he be the accomplice
in the Blue House?

263
00:22:44,780 --> 00:22:46,531
That means...

264
00:22:48,492 --> 00:22:50,660
If you were Agent Kim Jun-o

265
00:22:52,412 --> 00:22:55,373
and learned about the attack,
whom in the Blue House

266
00:22:56,500 --> 00:22:58,001
would you report to?

267
00:23:11,098 --> 00:23:12,974
This is Kang Dae-han of the security team.

268
00:23:13,183 --> 00:23:15,977
Is it possible to get a list
of the phone numbers that called

269
00:23:16,061 --> 00:23:18,855
the security team during the week
before the bombing?

270
00:23:19,648 --> 00:23:20,816
SPEECHES OF THE PRESIDENTS

271
00:23:27,739 --> 00:23:28,740
Take a look at this.

272
00:23:30,158 --> 00:23:32,786
This is a video
made by editing suggestions

273
00:23:32,869 --> 00:23:35,247
that were posted on the petition board.

274
00:23:36,456 --> 00:23:38,583
I need a house to get married.

275
00:23:38,917 --> 00:23:41,586
I'm looking to rent a house
in Seoul or Gyeonggi Province...

276
00:23:41,670 --> 00:23:43,380
But I'll need to get a loan

277
00:23:43,672 --> 00:23:45,257
and the conditions for a loan are strict.

278
00:23:45,924 --> 00:23:48,969
I may never get married in this state.

279
00:23:49,219 --> 00:23:51,555
It's been three years since I got married,

280
00:23:51,638 --> 00:23:53,473
but I can't even imagine having kids.

281
00:23:53,682 --> 00:23:55,851
My husband and I both have to work.

282
00:23:55,934 --> 00:23:58,645
I really hope the disability rating system
will be abolished.

283
00:23:59,229 --> 00:24:00,939
They say it will be,
but nothing has changed.

284
00:24:01,022 --> 00:24:02,858
However, there was a budget cut.

285
00:24:03,150 --> 00:24:05,235
I hope the government
can be more sensitive.

286
00:24:05,318 --> 00:24:06,403
I live in a different region

287
00:24:06,486 --> 00:24:09,906
and it's sad to see that only Seoul
has a safety system for women.

288
00:24:10,198 --> 00:24:12,200
I wish we had a safe
delivery system for women

289
00:24:12,284 --> 00:24:14,494
or a system to help us get home safely.

290
00:24:14,828 --> 00:24:18,915
I really wish Korea would become a country

291
00:24:19,583 --> 00:24:22,419
where old retirees can find new jobs.

292
00:24:22,502 --> 00:24:25,589
I'm thinking of adding this

293
00:24:26,464 --> 00:24:27,883
at the end of the press conference.

294
00:24:29,467 --> 00:24:33,680
These are suggestions made
after the bombing.

295
00:24:34,264 --> 00:24:39,227
It's the expectations, hope and vision
they have for President Park.

296
00:24:39,311 --> 00:24:40,687
I've been thinking about

297
00:24:41,563 --> 00:24:46,359
what the president should say
at the end of the press conference.

298
00:24:46,443 --> 00:24:47,360
Yes?

299
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:50,030
I gave it some thought.

300
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:56,286
What if he says something we can also use

301
00:24:56,369 --> 00:24:59,039
as a catchphrase
for his presidential campaign?

302
00:25:00,248 --> 00:25:01,208
Okay.

303
00:25:01,750 --> 00:25:03,043
Let's hear it.

304
00:25:03,210 --> 00:25:04,377
Okay.

305
00:25:07,964 --> 00:25:08,840
All right.

306
00:25:09,925 --> 00:25:12,886
This is a catchphrase

307
00:25:13,595 --> 00:25:15,972
with a vision for a welfare state
in the 21st century.

308
00:25:19,559 --> 00:25:20,810
"Let's all go

309
00:25:22,812 --> 00:25:24,105
to a happy nation."

310
00:25:28,276 --> 00:25:29,402
Something like that.

311
00:25:34,241 --> 00:25:35,325
Unbelievable.

312
00:25:37,494 --> 00:25:41,373
I know retro is the trend, but...

313
00:25:42,999 --> 00:25:44,793
I didn't like it much either.

314
00:25:46,419 --> 00:25:47,963
Next.

315
00:25:49,798 --> 00:25:51,216
This one

316
00:25:52,801 --> 00:25:54,344
is to show his will

317
00:25:55,095 --> 00:26:00,183
to reconstruct the nation
after the bombing.

318
00:26:01,810 --> 00:26:02,811
Here it is.

319
00:26:04,271 --> 00:26:06,731
"Fresh scenery

320
00:26:07,315 --> 00:26:09,401
in the Republic of Korea."

321
00:26:11,361 --> 00:26:13,655
That's not it, is it?

322
00:26:14,114 --> 00:26:16,574
It can't be. Right? I hope not.

323
00:26:25,959 --> 00:26:27,335
It's okay.

324
00:26:28,503 --> 00:26:31,131
Hiring experts at the right time

325
00:26:33,675 --> 00:26:36,511
is also an ability
the chief presidential secretary needs.

326
00:26:41,141 --> 00:26:42,225
Why don't we

327
00:26:43,268 --> 00:26:44,102
outsource it?

328
00:26:46,021 --> 00:26:47,397
Gosh, Secretary Han.

329
00:26:48,064 --> 00:26:48,982
This is

330
00:26:49,566 --> 00:26:50,442
the last one.

331
00:26:53,069 --> 00:26:54,404
I feel

332
00:26:56,239 --> 00:26:58,867
that the people

333
00:27:00,660 --> 00:27:01,661
should feel proud

334
00:27:02,871 --> 00:27:05,373
about overcoming the attack.

335
00:27:07,709 --> 00:27:08,960
Finally,

336
00:27:10,045 --> 00:27:11,338
"Our pride,

337
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:14,966
the Republic of Korea."

338
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:19,596
I like it.

339
00:27:22,891 --> 00:27:23,850
Nice.

340
00:27:29,773 --> 00:27:30,857
All right.

341
00:27:33,151 --> 00:27:34,194
I like it.

342
00:27:34,694 --> 00:27:36,404
-It's nice.
-Really?

343
00:27:36,488 --> 00:27:38,156
-Can we use the first one?
-No.

344
00:27:38,490 --> 00:27:40,158
That was a joke.

345
00:27:40,867 --> 00:27:42,786
It didn't sound like a joke.

346
00:27:43,453 --> 00:27:45,455
You sounded dead serious.

347
00:27:46,331 --> 00:27:47,624
I just thought of it.

348
00:27:48,041 --> 00:27:49,292
Of course you did.

349
00:27:49,376 --> 00:27:51,961
Would you like to go in for a minute?

350
00:27:52,337 --> 00:27:54,297
I think they're preparing
for the press conference.

351
00:27:56,966 --> 00:27:59,677
I'll be interrupting them. Let's go.

352
00:28:35,964 --> 00:28:37,257
Do you like it?

353
00:28:39,467 --> 00:28:40,510
What's this?

354
00:28:41,928 --> 00:28:43,930
See if you like it.

355
00:28:51,479 --> 00:28:52,605
I...

356
00:28:53,857 --> 00:28:55,900
don't know yet.

357
00:28:57,694 --> 00:28:58,695
I'm not sure if you

358
00:29:00,363 --> 00:29:04,075
can really become president
like people say you will,

359
00:29:07,245 --> 00:29:09,497
or if I'll be able to stand living here

360
00:29:10,874 --> 00:29:12,792
if we move back in.

361
00:29:18,339 --> 00:29:19,299
However,

362
00:29:20,133 --> 00:29:21,342
there is one thing I know.

363
00:29:24,220 --> 00:29:26,389
It's your decision,

364
00:29:27,182 --> 00:29:29,476
so it can't be wrong.

365
00:29:30,477 --> 00:29:32,812
You'll always be right.

366
00:29:36,441 --> 00:29:38,359
Is it my birthday today?

367
00:29:39,027 --> 00:29:42,447
You gave me a present
and shared sweet words of wisdom.

368
00:29:42,530 --> 00:29:43,907
I got lucky today.

369
00:29:46,159 --> 00:29:46,993
You...

370
00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:52,457
always look for the best answer
when there isn't a right one.

371
00:29:53,333 --> 00:29:55,460
You never give up.

372
00:29:58,505 --> 00:30:00,715
I won't be of much help,

373
00:30:02,550 --> 00:30:04,344
but during everything

374
00:30:05,053 --> 00:30:06,304
you go through,

375
00:30:07,222 --> 00:30:08,306
I'll be there by your side,

376
00:30:10,183 --> 00:30:12,560
especially when no one is applauding you.

377
00:30:15,647 --> 00:30:16,773
Remember it.

378
00:30:20,985 --> 00:30:23,071
And today

379
00:30:24,280 --> 00:30:25,740
isn't your birthday.

380
00:30:26,449 --> 00:30:27,617
It's our wedding anniversary.

381
00:30:37,585 --> 00:30:41,005
Honey. Wait a minute. Listen to me.

382
00:30:42,173 --> 00:30:46,719
President Park Mu-jin will end
his official schedule as acting president

383
00:30:46,803 --> 00:30:50,807
for the past 30 days
with the press conference this afternoon.

384
00:30:50,890 --> 00:30:54,269
He is currently
the leading presidential candidate.

385
00:30:54,352 --> 00:30:55,854
What would you do, Na-gyeong?

386
00:30:57,605 --> 00:31:00,275
Let's say you're
the leading presidential candidate.

387
00:31:01,150 --> 00:31:02,277
Someone you know,

388
00:31:02,944 --> 00:31:05,071
but aren't aware of
is the mastermind behind the attack.

389
00:31:06,322 --> 00:31:09,325
That's what the bombers said,
but it wasn't verified.

390
00:31:09,409 --> 00:31:11,119
What if it's true?

391
00:31:12,370 --> 00:31:14,122
Can he reveal the truth

392
00:31:15,248 --> 00:31:17,709
when all that power
is practically within his reach?

393
00:31:23,131 --> 00:31:25,383
PRESIDENT PARK OFFICIALLY
JOINS PRESIDENTIAL RACE

394
00:31:29,178 --> 00:31:30,013
Na-gyeong,

395
00:31:30,722 --> 00:31:32,599
do you know what I just found out?

396
00:31:33,433 --> 00:31:36,394
Ji-won, you should shake that habit.

397
00:31:36,477 --> 00:31:38,980
Don't start with a question
when you're reporting to a superior.

398
00:31:39,731 --> 00:31:40,732
Sit down.

399
00:31:41,858 --> 00:31:43,985
Whether I start with a question
or a statement,

400
00:31:45,111 --> 00:31:48,740
just focus on what I have to tell you.

401
00:31:49,949 --> 00:31:52,577
Mr. Kim and the other anti-North spies

402
00:31:53,328 --> 00:31:56,956
filed a suit for damages
against the country in 2011.

403
00:31:57,040 --> 00:31:58,541
And? Did they win?

404
00:31:58,625 --> 00:31:59,584
They lost.

405
00:32:00,585 --> 00:32:03,880
A quite reputable human rights lawyer
represented them

406
00:32:05,048 --> 00:32:06,382
and that lawyer

407
00:32:07,133 --> 00:32:08,676
was someone we know.

408
00:32:18,728 --> 00:32:20,021
Who was the lawyer?

409
00:32:31,908 --> 00:32:33,201
Hello, Mr. Kang.

410
00:32:33,493 --> 00:32:34,661
What...

411
00:32:40,667 --> 00:32:43,169
March 4, on the morning of the bombing,
Agent Kim Jun-o

412
00:32:43,878 --> 00:32:46,047
called the Deputy of the Security Team.

413
00:32:48,758 --> 00:32:50,093
Are you saying

414
00:32:51,636 --> 00:32:53,846
that he's the accomplice
within the Blue House

415
00:32:53,930 --> 00:32:55,640
who covered up Agent Kim's report?

416
00:32:55,723 --> 00:32:56,975
My guess is

417
00:32:57,642 --> 00:32:59,394
that after he received Agent Kim's call,

418
00:32:59,477 --> 00:33:01,604
he discussed it with another person
at the Blue House.

419
00:33:02,397 --> 00:33:04,273
With his mind at ease,

420
00:33:04,357 --> 00:33:06,067
he then escorted the President out.

421
00:33:09,487 --> 00:33:11,948
Through the cameras, I retraced his steps

422
00:33:12,031 --> 00:33:15,827
before he left for
the National Assembly Building that day.

423
00:33:15,910 --> 00:33:17,036
Here.

424
00:33:21,624 --> 00:33:22,709
This is Deputy Kim Jong-min

425
00:33:22,792 --> 00:33:25,003
of the Security Team
who died in the bombing.

426
00:33:29,132 --> 00:33:31,592
If this person,
who he reported the attack to,

427
00:33:32,218 --> 00:33:33,761
didn't disregard the warning

428
00:33:34,262 --> 00:33:35,805
and cover it up,

429
00:33:36,514 --> 00:33:38,141
the bombing

430
00:33:40,810 --> 00:33:42,854
may have never occurred.

431
00:34:00,496 --> 00:34:03,583
ANTI-NORTH SPIES
LOSE IN COURT AGAINST STATE

432
00:34:06,210 --> 00:34:07,879
The lawyer of the case...

433
00:34:08,463 --> 00:34:10,548
It's the same person
who's currently at the Blue House,

434
00:34:11,049 --> 00:34:11,924
right?

435
00:34:16,012 --> 00:34:17,388
It was Chief Presidential Secretary

436
00:34:18,473 --> 00:34:19,640
Han Ju-seung.

437
00:34:37,658 --> 00:34:38,576
ATTORNEY HAN JU-SEUNG

438
00:34:38,659 --> 00:34:40,787
The attorney of that case.

439
00:34:41,454 --> 00:34:43,790
The person who ordered you
to help Mr. Kim escape.

440
00:34:48,961 --> 00:34:50,213
That attorney.

441
00:34:50,797 --> 00:34:53,216
Is Secretary Han Ju-seung

442
00:34:54,258 --> 00:34:55,426
the mastermind?

443
00:35:05,436 --> 00:35:07,355
Can you believe it?

444
00:35:07,855 --> 00:35:09,148
That's absurd.

445
00:35:09,232 --> 00:35:11,943
But it's too noisy.

446
00:35:12,026 --> 00:35:13,236
Seriously.

447
00:35:18,199 --> 00:35:19,492
Hope is a good thing.

448
00:35:20,993 --> 00:35:22,745
It masks the hardship

449
00:35:23,371 --> 00:35:26,415
and gives you the strength to start over.

450
00:35:27,416 --> 00:35:29,836
It also gives you the courage

451
00:35:30,002 --> 00:35:31,254
to live a new life.

452
00:35:33,214 --> 00:35:34,966
To them,

453
00:35:36,050 --> 00:35:38,678
you're their greatest hope.

454
00:35:38,761 --> 00:35:40,513
Oh, I get it now.

455
00:35:40,596 --> 00:35:41,681
Unbelievable.

456
00:35:41,764 --> 00:35:43,266
Gosh.

457
00:35:43,349 --> 00:35:45,601
It's the same hope I tasted

458
00:35:45,685 --> 00:35:49,564
when I met President Yang
back when I was a public prosecutor.

459
00:35:50,731 --> 00:35:51,732
And now,

460
00:35:53,025 --> 00:35:54,819
I'm feeling the same hope

461
00:35:55,695 --> 00:35:56,821
with you.

462
00:36:06,581 --> 00:36:08,040
Could I have some of your time?

463
00:36:12,003 --> 00:36:13,504
There's something I'd like to discuss.

464
00:36:39,447 --> 00:36:41,073
On the day of the bombing,

465
00:36:41,824 --> 00:36:45,536
the Blue House Security Team
received a report of a potential attack.

466
00:36:47,079 --> 00:36:50,166
The report came from

467
00:36:50,708 --> 00:36:52,126
Agent Kim Jun-o of the NIS.

468
00:36:53,628 --> 00:36:57,089
Agent Kim Jun-o reported to
the Deputy of the Security Team

469
00:36:57,381 --> 00:37:00,676
that the top secret file of OP 5015-18

470
00:37:01,052 --> 00:37:03,095
was in the hands of those
who could do harm

471
00:37:03,846 --> 00:37:07,308
and that they were plotting to attack
the National Assembly Building

472
00:37:07,516 --> 00:37:09,602
as it is demonstrated on the file.

473
00:37:10,937 --> 00:37:12,396
Even though Deputy Kim

474
00:37:12,980 --> 00:37:14,732
was informed of this attack,

475
00:37:15,524 --> 00:37:18,903
he still escorted President Yang
to the National Assembly Building.

476
00:37:20,947 --> 00:37:23,491
Why do you think he did?

477
00:37:30,498 --> 00:37:31,582
It's because

478
00:37:32,375 --> 00:37:34,252
someone told him it was a hoax report

479
00:37:35,086 --> 00:37:36,921
and put his mind at ease.

480
00:37:38,130 --> 00:37:39,423
That day,

481
00:37:40,424 --> 00:37:43,636
after Deputy Kim
received Agent Kim's call,

482
00:37:44,011 --> 00:37:46,222
he met with someone before leaving for

483
00:37:47,056 --> 00:37:48,057
the National Assembly.

484
00:37:48,140 --> 00:37:49,558
It was me.

485
00:38:03,322 --> 00:38:04,949
Do you know where Secretary Han went?

486
00:38:05,116 --> 00:38:07,034
He was here just a minute ago.

487
00:38:08,160 --> 00:38:10,997
He was talking to President Park.

488
00:38:11,080 --> 00:38:12,331
Maybe they left together.

489
00:38:12,915 --> 00:38:14,417
Mr. Cha, don't you know?

490
00:38:15,001 --> 00:38:18,004
I saw them together
a moment ago too, but...

491
00:38:19,338 --> 00:38:21,340
Gosh.

492
00:38:21,507 --> 00:38:22,967
Is something up?

493
00:38:23,801 --> 00:38:24,802
Why?

494
00:38:26,178 --> 00:38:27,722
What was your reason?

495
00:38:29,265 --> 00:38:30,975
You knew about the bombing.

496
00:38:31,767 --> 00:38:34,645
President Yang was your friend
and a political ally--

497
00:38:34,729 --> 00:38:35,730
This country

498
00:38:36,564 --> 00:38:39,358
isn't worthy of a President like him.

499
00:38:46,407 --> 00:38:48,367
Impatient, selfish,

500
00:38:48,534 --> 00:38:49,744
and greedy.

501
00:38:50,578 --> 00:38:52,955
The people of this nation
don't know how to be patient.

502
00:38:53,789 --> 00:38:55,041
To those people,

503
00:38:55,124 --> 00:38:57,877
President Yang and his view of democracy

504
00:38:59,086 --> 00:39:00,880
was more than what they deserved.

505
00:39:02,256 --> 00:39:04,008
President Yang's approval ratings

506
00:39:04,759 --> 00:39:07,553
during his time in the office proves that.

507
00:39:08,596 --> 00:39:10,056
President Yang and I...

508
00:39:12,224 --> 00:39:13,517
failed.

509
00:39:15,936 --> 00:39:17,772
I devoted my life

510
00:39:19,523 --> 00:39:21,400
and put my faith
in the people of this nation.

511
00:39:23,235 --> 00:39:24,653
They are the ones

512
00:39:26,447 --> 00:39:27,740
who betrayed us first.

513
00:39:29,241 --> 00:39:30,242
So...

514
00:39:31,577 --> 00:39:33,788
Was blowing up
the National Assembly Building

515
00:39:34,413 --> 00:39:37,500
your way of seeking revenge
against the people?

516
00:39:37,666 --> 00:39:38,876
I decided upon

517
00:39:40,544 --> 00:39:42,755
a governing style
which well suited this nation.

518
00:39:45,132 --> 00:39:47,802
The most formidable type of power

519
00:39:50,262 --> 00:39:52,348
is fear and terror.

520
00:39:56,268 --> 00:39:57,561
The people

521
00:39:57,895 --> 00:40:00,564
fear and obey those

522
00:40:00,815 --> 00:40:03,526
who reign over or govern them.

523
00:40:04,193 --> 00:40:06,153
That's what I learned

524
00:40:08,072 --> 00:40:09,281
through our failures.

525
00:40:10,533 --> 00:40:12,576
By choosing someone like Minister Oh

526
00:40:12,827 --> 00:40:14,328
to govern this country?

527
00:40:15,871 --> 00:40:17,373
Until

528
00:40:18,082 --> 00:40:21,419
he won over the people
and became elected as the new President,

529
00:40:22,044 --> 00:40:24,046
you needed someone to manage this ship.

530
00:40:25,214 --> 00:40:28,592
It's why you needed a puppet
who didn't know anything about politics.

531
00:40:31,262 --> 00:40:32,888
You used me

532
00:40:33,889 --> 00:40:35,015
to complete

533
00:40:35,683 --> 00:40:37,685
your grand attack

534
00:40:40,813 --> 00:40:43,941
by joining forces with those
who you have been opposed to

535
00:40:45,109 --> 00:40:46,277
all your life.

536
00:40:49,738 --> 00:40:50,906
None of them

537
00:40:52,491 --> 00:40:54,702
are left in this world now.

538
00:40:56,203 --> 00:40:57,830
From this moment on,

539
00:40:58,914 --> 00:41:00,916
my plan is for you to take this seat

540
00:41:01,667 --> 00:41:02,877
as Korea's President.

541
00:41:04,837 --> 00:41:06,547
Do you want to be remembered

542
00:41:07,381 --> 00:41:09,842
as the one who completed this bombing

543
00:41:10,259 --> 00:41:11,260
or...

544
00:41:12,261 --> 00:41:14,680
would you like to be remembered as

545
00:41:15,097 --> 00:41:17,433
the admirable President
who restored this nation?

546
00:41:19,643 --> 00:41:21,187
It's your choice.

